						 Rory McIlroy holds his putter in his mouth on the 18th green after enduring a frustrating final round at the World Cup alongside
playing partner Graeme McDowell 
						 
		 
	 
             
                World Cup blues for off-key Macs 
             
     
IRELAND'S 'soul brothers', Rory McIlroy and Graeme McDowell, once again wound up singing the World Cup blues at Mission Hills yesterday. 

 
					 
						 
	 
				
             
         
             
                Clarke woes continue Down Under 
             
     
	 

 
Like many first-time Major-winners, Darren Clarke has struggled to make an impact at tournaments since his stunning victory at July's British Open in Sandwich. 

 

 
	 
             
                Time running out for Maybin 
             
     
	 

 
GARETH MAYBIN'S grim battle to save his European Tour card took another turn for the worse yesterday as a tie for 53rd in the South African Open dropped the Ulsterman another two places down the Order of Merit to 120th. 

 

 
	 
             
                Nation's favourite retains the faith of those who know him best 
             
     
	
				By Dermot Gilleece 
			 

 
While we worry and wonder as to what the future may hold for Pádraig Harrington, a long-time pal made a reassuring prediction about the country's much-loved golfer. "I expect him to continue to have a successful career right up to senior level," is the view of prospective Ryder Cup captain Paul McGinley. 

 

 
	 
				
             
         
             
                McIlroy and McDowell 68 lift Ireland in World Cup  
             
     
	 

 
IRELAND joined Australia at the top of the World Cup leaderboard after a 68 from Rory McIlroy and Graeme McDowell in today's foursomes lifted them to 13 under par. 

 

 
	 
				
             
         
             
                Clarke hoping hard work will bring change in fortunes 
             
     
	
				By George Williams 
			 

 
DARREN CLARKE will be trying to end what he calls an "incredibly frustrating" spell in the Australian PGA Championship at Coolum this week. 

 

 
	 
             
                Aussies take lead over Ireland and Scotland in golf  World Cup 
             
     
	 

 
AUSTRALIAN duo Richard Green and Brendan Jones carded a superb 61 to take a two-shot lead over Ireland and Scotland after the first round of the World Cup in China. 

 

 
	 
             
                McIlroy sets alarm bells ringing for Irish Open 
             
     
	
				By William S Callahan 
			 

 
RORY McILROY has no trouble making tough decisions... as his long-time mentor, friend and former agent Chubby Chandler doubtless will attest. 

 

 
	 
             
                Els chasing sixth national title success 
             
     
	 

 
Gareth Maybin is the only Irish golfer teeing it up today in the South African Open at the Serengeti GC, where Ernie Els is bidding for his sixth title. 

 

 
	 
             
                Clarke aims to shine Down Under 
             
     
	
				By Mark Garrod 
			 

 
Darren Clarke will be trying to end what he calls an "incredibly frustrating" spell in this week's Australian PGA Championship at Coolum. 

 

 
				 

    
    
	
